              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is an 8-year-old boy from the Czech Republic who is brought in by a parent because of acute diarrhea that started suddenly and has kept him close to the bathroom through the day [SNOMED:A09.0]. His parent says the stools have been loose and frequent, and they are worried because infectious gastroenteritis commonly presents this way [SNOMED:A09.0]. He looks tired and less playful than usual, sitting quietly on the exam table and asking for water between questions. There has been no report of bloody stool today, though hemorrhagic diarrhea can occur with this condition [SNOMED:A09.0].\n\nAt baseline, {patientName} is an active primary-school child who enjoys football after school, building LEGO sets, and playing video games with friends from his neighborhood. He lives with his parents and a younger sibling, and usually eats regular family meals and brings a packed snack to school. Since becoming ill, he has stayed home, has not wanted to run around, and has been resting on the couch near a parent.\n\nHis parent describes him as usually healthy, energetic, and sociable, but over the last day he has become clingier and more subdued because of the diarrhea [SNOMED:A09.0]. He has been able to sip fluids but has had reduced appetite. The family came in mainly to make sure he does not get dehydrated and to understand whether this is an infectious stomach illness causing his diarrhea [SNOMED:A09.0]."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:d6381b08-6d46-46ef-a321-097a4f4bbe67",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
